];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: 'TRY 11,000-17,000', annual: 'TRY 132,000-204,000' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (70-74)', monthly: 'TRY 15,000-23,000', annual: 'TRY 180,000-276,000' },
  { category: 'International Insurance (75-79)', monthly: 'TRY 20,000-30,000', annual: 'TRY 240,000-360,000' },
  { category: 'Turkish Private Hospital', monthly: 'Pay per visit', annual: 'TRY 500-1,500/visit' },
  { category: 'Turkish Public (SGK)', monthly: 'Contribution', annual: 'Subsidized care' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Turkey 2026 | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Turkey. Mediterranean lifestyle, excellent hospitals, affordable living, and coverage for expats 65+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Turkey"
  subheadline="Turkey offers Mediterranean lifestyle, excellent private healthcare, rich history, and affordable living—a popular retirement destination with dedicated residence pathways."
  heroImage="/images/countries/turkey-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Senior Plans →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Turkey</h2>
  <p>
    Turkey bridges Europe and Asia with Mediterranean beaches, ancient history (Ephesus, Cappadocia), world-class hospitals, and affordable living. The Turkish lira devaluation has made costs extremely attractive for foreign pension holders. Large British and German expat communities are well-established.
  </p>

  <p>
    Antalya and the Turkish Riviera offer beach retirement with mountains nearby. Istanbul provides world-city culture and excellent hospitals. Bodrum and Fethiye attract sailing enthusiasts. Alanya has large European expat communities. Each region offers distinct character and strong healthcare.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Excellent private; JCI-accredited hospitals</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> Turkish; English in tourist/expat areas</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of Living:</strong> TRY 30,000-80,000/month (~$900-2,400); very affordable</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Mediterranean coast; continental interior</li>
      <li><strong>Medical Tourism:</strong> Major destination for procedures</li>
      <li><strong>Character:</strong> East meets West; rich history; welcoming</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Turkey Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Turkey has excellent private healthcare—many hospitals are JCI-accredited (international gold standard). Istanbul Acibadem, Memorial, and American Hospital are world-class. Antalya has multiple excellent private hospitals serving medical tourists. Quality rivals European standards at lower cost.
  </p>

  <p>
    Public healthcare (SGK system) is available to residents who contribute. Quality varies—major city public hospitals are adequate; rural areas less so. Most expats use private healthcare. Medical tourism is a major industry—Turkey is competitive for procedures from hair transplants to cardiac surgery.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">SGK Registration Option</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800 mb-0">
      Residents can join Turkey SGK (Social Security) system by contributing monthly payments. This provides access to public healthcare. Many expats maintain international insurance for private hospitals while using SGK for routine care.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="visa-requirements">Visa Options for Seniors</h2>
  <p>
    Turkey offers attractive options for retirees:
  </p>

  <h3>Short-Term Residence Permit</h3>
  <p>
    For those not working—demonstrate income of approximately $500+/month, health insurance, and accommodation. Valid 1-2 years, renewable. Most common pathway for retirees.
  </p>

  <h3>Property Investment</h3>
  <p>
    Buying property worth $75,000+ (varies by city) allows residence application. Property ownership is straightforward for foreigners in most areas.
  </p>

  <h3>Long-Term Residence</h3>
  <p>
    After 8 years of continuous residence, eligible for long-term residence permit. Provides more secure status.
  </p>

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance requirements for Turkey:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Residence permit:</strong> Health insurance mandatory for application</li>
    <li><strong>Coverage level:</strong> Must meet Turkish government minimum standards</li>
    <li><strong>SGK option:</strong> Can join public system after residence established</li>
    <li><strong>International:</strong> Typically accepted and often preferred</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Insurance Strategy for Turkey</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800 mb-0">
      International insurance is essential for residence applications and recommended for access to excellent private hospitals. Some combine with SGK registration for comprehensive coverage.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
  <p>
    For seniors in Turkey, international coverage with local hospital access works well:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3>Why These Providers Work for Turkey</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Good Turkish hospital network, widely recognized</li>
    <li><strong>BUPA Global:</strong> Highest entry age (79), comprehensive coverage</li>
    <li><strong>Now Health:</strong> Competitive pricing for Turkey region</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Strong Mediterranean coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Get Personalized Senior Quotes</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Compare coverage from providers accepted for Turkish residence.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get BUPA Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs for Turkey are moderate given excellent healthcare quality:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Higher deductibles:</strong> Turkish private care is affordable; high deductible works</li>
    <li><strong>SGK supplement:</strong> Public system for routine; international for serious</li>
    <li><strong>Regional coverage:</strong> Turkey + EU focused rather than worldwide</li>
    <li><strong>Medical tourism:</strong> Use Turkey excellent hospitals for procedures</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 1: British Beach Retiree, 68</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> £1,800/month pension. Retiring to Antalya. Seeking sun and value.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Short-term residence permit. Cigna Global with UK coverage.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> Cigna ~TRY 14,000/month (~£350). Mediterranean lifestyle with excellent healthcare.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 2: German Couple, Both 72</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> Combined pension €2,800/month. Buying property in Alanya.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Property-based residence. BUPA Global for both.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> BUPA ~TRY 35,000/month combined (~€900). German-speaking support; excellent value.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 3: American Culture Seeker, 66</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> $2,500/month pension. Moving to Istanbul for history and culture.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Short-term residence. Now Health covering Turkey + US.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> Now Health ~TRY 12,000/month (~$360). World-city living at developing-world prices.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Turkey safe for retirees?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Generally safe. Tourist and expat areas are well-policed. Political protests occur in major cities but rarely affect expats. Southeast border regions should be avoided. Most retirees in coastal/tourist areas live comfortably.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How affordable is Turkey?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Extremely affordable for foreign pension holders. Lira devaluation means Western pensions go much further. Quality restaurants $10-20 per person. Excellent apartments rent for $400-800/month.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How good are Turkish hospitals?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Excellent—Turkey is a major medical tourism destination. JCI-accredited hospitals in Istanbul, Ankara, and Antalya. Equipment is modern; many doctors trained in US/Europe. Quality rivals developed countries.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get by with English?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        In tourist/expat areas—yes. Outside these areas, Turkish is essential. Healthcare in private hospitals usually has English-speaking staff.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Ready to Compare Options?</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Get quotes from providers accepted for Turkish residence permits.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Cigna Quote</a>
      <a href="/go/now-health" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Get Now Health Quote</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-0">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Insurance requirements, visa regulations, and healthcare access rules change regularly. Always verify current requirements with Turkish authorities and consult with a licensed insurance professional.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
